If Slack or Hipchat is costing you $5 per person per month times 20 people, that's $100 per month or $1,200 per year. So the knowledge base is actually cheaper!

These are just some quick back-of-the-envelope calculations to give you some idea of the kind of numbers you might want to look at. You can find more information about knowledge bases in this article:

* https://support.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/articles/200552056-Knowledge-bases-101-What-they-are-and-why-you-need-one

It's also helpful to point out that documentation can be used to help support customers as well as internal teams. Here's an example:

* https://www.intercom.com/blog/how-to-create-a-knowledge-base/

A knowledge base is a great way to provide self-service support to customers. This article describes how to create a knowledge base for Intercom, but the principles apply to any knowledge base.

Finally, it's important to remember that documentation can be written in a way that's easy to understand. Here are some tips for writing documentation that's clear and concise:

* Use plain language. Avoid jargon and technical terms that might be confusing to someone who isn't familiar with the topic.
* Use short sentences and paragraphs. Long sentences and paragraphs are hard to read and understand. Break them up into smaller pieces.
* Use headings and subheadings to structure your content. This makes it easier for readers to scan the document and find the information they're looking for.
* Use images and videos to illustrate your points. Visuals can help readers understand complex concepts more easily than text alone.
* Use links to provide additional information. If there's a related article or resource that will help readers understand your topic better, include a link to it.
output_2:
It’s easy to forget that documentation is for people who aren’t you.  When you’re writing it, it’s easy to assume that people know the same things you do, that they’re familiar with the same concepts, and that they’re as motivated as you are to dig around and find the right information.  But that’s often not the case.

When people come to your documentation, they don’t know what they don’t know.  They’re hoping that your documentation will fill in the gaps in their knowledge.  If your documentation doesn’t help them, they’ll be frustrated and give up.  So your job as a writer is to help them fill in those gaps.

To do that, you need to understand what those gaps are.  In other words, you need to understand your users.  Who are they?  What do they need to know?  How do they go about learning new things?

If you don’t know the answers to those questions, ask them.  Talk to your users.  Ask them what questions they have, and why they have them.  If you can’t talk to your users, find someone who can and ask them to report back to you.  The more you know about your users, the easier it will be for you to help them.

And remember, the goal isn’t to help them use your product, but to help them solve their problems.  If your documentation doesn’t help them solve their problems, they won’t come back.

instruction: Why do high class restaurants serve such small portions?
output_1:
A few reasons:

* It's fashionable to eat "light" and "healthy" and smaller portions seem to fit into that.
* Higher end restaurants have higher rent and thus need to charge more for their meals.  Serving smaller portions allows them to charge more without people feeling like they're being ripped off for a small amount of food.
* When they do serve large portions it's usually as a special, or if you order multiple courses.
* Restaurants need to turn their tables more quickly so they can make more money from their space.  If you order a large meal it's going to take longer to eat, and they'll have that table occupied for longer.  If you order a small meal you'll be done eating more quickly, and they can get more people into their space in a given period of time.

A side effect of this is that they can also charge more for the appetizers and desserts since they're going to be smaller portions.

There are some downsides though:

* People will eat more if the portions are large.  This means that they'll end up eating more calories than they need and will gain weight.
* People will spend more money if the portions are large.  This means that they'll end up spending more money than they need to and will end up eating more calories than they need.

The portion size of food is decided by the chef, who typically aims to achieve a balance between flavor and appearance, while also taking into account the overall price of the dish. 

* Appearance: The chef wants the dish to look good. A small portion size is one way to achieve this, since the food will appear more dense, and people will perceive it as more expensive. The chef may also use garnishes and other visual effects to make the food look more appealing.
* Flavor: The chef wants the food to taste good. Smaller portions allow the chef to use higher quality ingredients, and to prepare the food in a way that brings out the full flavor of the ingredients. 
* Price: The price of the dish is determined by the cost of the ingredients and the amount of labor required to prepare it. Smaller portions mean that the restaurant can charge a higher price per dish, which allows them to recover the cost of expensive ingredients and pay the chef a higher salary. 

These factors are interrelated. For example, a dish that looks good and has a strong flavor may require more expensive ingredients, which means the restaurant can charge a higher price for it. However, it’s important for the restaurant to strike a balance between these factors, since customers will choose a dish based on the price and how it looks.

Some chefs believe that small portions can enhance the dining experience. This is because people tend to eat more slowly when they are presented with a small amount of food. As a result, they can enjoy the flavor of the food more, and the chef can prepare the next course before the previous course is finished. 

The portion size of food is also influenced by cultural and social factors. For example, in Japan, it’s considered polite to eat slowly and leave some food on the plate, whereas in the US, it’s common to eat quickly and clean the plate. In addition, high-class restaurants typically serve small portions because people expect this when they pay a high price for a meal.

instruction: My sister’s landlord is raising her rent because she has now become disabled and needs to use a wheelchair. Is this legal?
output_1:
In most cases, yes, it is legal for a landlord to raise the rent of a tenant if the tenant has become disabled.  The landlord has the right to raise the rent to market rate, but must allow the tenant a reasonable amount of time to find another place to live.  In some cases, the landlord can be charged with discrimination if they raise the rent of a disabled tenant but not a non-disabled tenant.

In the US, landlords must abide by the Americans With Disabilities Act (ADA), which prohibits discrimination against people with disabilities in housing and in other areas of public life.  Under the ADA, a landlord cannot refuse to rent to a disabled person, cannot deny a reasonable request for a reasonable accommodation, and cannot charge a disabled person more than the going rate.  In most cases, the landlord cannot raise the rent of a disabled tenant unless the landlord would be allowed to do the same to a non-disabled tenant.  If the landlord raises the rent of a disabled tenant but not of a non-disabled tenant, they can be charged with discrimination.

In most states in the US, the landlord must give the tenant at least 30 days written notice before raising the rent.  The tenant has the right to dispute the increase in rent by taking the landlord to small claims court.  If the tenant wins, they are entitled to recover double the amount of the rent increase.  If the landlord wins, they are entitled to recover the amount of the rent increase.

In most cases, the landlord is allowed to raise the rent of a disabled tenant if they would be allowed to raise the rent of a non-disabled tenant.  If the landlord is not allowed to raise the rent of a non-disabled tenant, then they cannot raise the rent of the disabled tenant.  This is because the landlord is discriminating against the disabled tenant if they raise the rent of a disabled tenant but not a non-disabled tenant.  The landlord can be charged with discrimination if they raise the rent of a disabled tenant but not a non-disabled tenant.
output_2:
This sounds like a situation that may violate the federal Fair Housing Act (FHA). Under the FHA, it is illegal for a landlord to refuse to rent to, or to discriminate against, a person because of that person’s disability. This includes, for example, refusing to rent to someone because they need an “assistive device” such as a wheelchair, or refusing to make a “reasonable accommodation” to a tenant’s disability (for example, if a tenant’s disability prevents them from using the stairs, and the landlord refuses to install a wheelchair ramp).

The FHA also requires landlords to allow tenants to make “reasonable modifications” to their rental unit (such as widening doorways or installing grab bars) if the tenant needs these modifications to use and enjoy their rental unit. However, landlords are not required to make these modifications; if a landlord refuses to make a reasonable modification, the tenant may be able to file a complaint with the Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD) or take legal action against the landlord.

In addition, many states and cities have laws that prohibit housing discrimination based on disability. These laws may offer additional protections for tenants with disabilities.

If your sister’s landlord is violating the FHA or other fair housing laws, she may be able to file a complaint with HUD or take legal action against the landlord. She should contact an attorney or housing rights organization for more information about her legal options.

instruction: Conservatives often argue that social welfare programs encourage single motherhood and illegitimacy by replacing the necessity of marriage with dependency on the state. What does research have to say?

Social welfare programs do not promote single motherhood or illegitimacy. In fact, welfare programs can decrease single motherhood and illegitimacy.

In the 1970s, women began to challenge this requirement, and the requirement was eventually removed.  After the requirement was removed, welfare enrollment among single mothers increased.  This happened because when single mothers were required to get married, they were less likely to have children out of wedlock.  In other words, the requirement was encouraging marriage, not discouraging it.

Welfare programs have also been shown to reduce single motherhood and illegitimacy in other countries.  For example, a study of welfare programs in Canada found that "welfare programs have not contributed to an increase in illegitimacy in Canada."  Another study of welfare programs in Australia found that "the welfare system has not contributed to an increase in single motherhood."

In conclusion, welfare programs do not promote single motherhood or illegitimacy.  In fact, welfare programs can actually decrease single motherhood and illegitimacy.
output_2:

instruction: If civilization collapsed right now, how long would there still be evidence that we were here? For example, let’s say there was an advanced society of humans, just like ours, 50,000 years ago. Would there be any evidence left of their existence?
output_1:
There are a lot of factors that influence the longevity of evidence of civilization. Here are some of the factors that might influence how long any evidence of civilization lasts, in order of decreasing influence:

* Preservation. Some forms of evidence are more durable than others. Stone tools, cave paintings, and metal artifacts can last for thousands of years, while structures made from perishable materials like wood and thatch are much less likely to last that long. Similarly, paper and textiles can last for centuries under ideal conditions, but may disintegrate within a few decades if exposed to moisture, heat, or other damaging conditions.

* Environment. Weather, climate, and environmental conditions can have a big impact on the longevity of evidence of civilization. Areas with moderate temperatures and low humidity tend to preserve evidence better than hot, humid climates. For example, many of the ancient sites in Egypt have been preserved for thousands of years by the dry desert climate, while sites in Mesopotamia and other areas with more humid climates have been less well-preserved. Similarly, evidence buried under soil or sediment may be better preserved than evidence exposed to the elements.

* Destruction. Human activity can also play a role in the longevity of evidence of civilization. Sites that are actively maintained, such as archaeological digs and historical sites, may have their evidence preserved for centuries or even millennia. However, sites that are left unattended may be vulnerable to vandalism, looting, and other forms of destruction. Similarly, evidence that is exposed to the elements is more likely to be destroyed by natural processes than evidence that is buried or otherwise protected.

In conclusion, there is no definitive answer to the question of how long evidence of civilization will last. It depends on a variety of factors, including the type of evidence, the environment, and the level of protection and preservation. However, it is possible that evidence of civilization could last for thousands of years, even in the absence of active preservation efforts.
output_2:
That’s a very hard question to answer.  The only reason we know about ancient civilizations like the Egyptians and Mayans is because they developed writing.  We’ve found some pyramids and some stone buildings that we think were temples.  But most of the evidence we have is written on things like pottery, stone tablets, and paper.  Without writing, most of what we know about ancient civilizations would be lost forever.

So if civilization collapsed right now, most of the evidence would disappear within a few thousand years.  The buildings would fall apart and the land would be reclaimed by nature.  The written records would decay or be destroyed by fires.  The only things that might last for thousands of years are metal artifacts like tools and weapons.  But even they would eventually rust away.  It’s possible that some fossils or stone tools might be found by future humans, but it’s unlikely that they would be able to figure out who made them.

So if civilization collapsed tomorrow, most of the evidence would be gone within a few thousand years.  But there might be some small traces that would last for thousands of years.

instruction: I live in the Midwest of U.S., where we love using salt to de-ice our roads. This causes quite a bit of rusting on the underside of cars. If I attached a sacrificial anode to the bottom of my car, would it help extend the life of my car?
output_1:
This is a great idea, and would help in reducing the rusting of your car, but only for a short while.

The idea behind sacrificial anodes is that the anode will corrode away instead of the protected metal, sacrificing itself for the good of the protected metal.

The anode material is chosen to have a more negative reduction potential than the protected metal. So for instance, if you were protecting a piece of steel, you would want to use zinc as the anode material. Zinc has a more negative reduction potential than steel. In other words, zinc is more easily oxidized than steel. Thus, when the car starts to rust, the zinc anode will start to corrode, instead of the steel underneath.

But the problem is that this only works until the anode material is completely consumed. At that point, the steel underneath will begin to corrode again. So while a sacrificial anode is a good idea, it is only a temporary fix. You would need to keep replacing the anode as it corrodes away.

There are several places where this is done quite well. For instance, most water heaters have a sacrificial anode inside the tank, to protect the steel tank from corrosion. The anode rod is usually made of zinc, and as it corrodes away, the steel tank is protected. Once the anode is gone, the steel tank will start to corrode, and you'll need to replace the water heater.

So the answer to your question is: Yes, it would help reduce the rusting of your car, but only for a short while.

That is because it has a higher tendency to oxidize than the structure it is protecting, and when it oxidizes, it will grab electrons from the structure it is protecting.  This means the anode will corrode instead of the structure it is protecting.

This works because of the spontaneity of oxidation reactions.  Oxidation reactions are always spontaneous, except in very acidic solutions.  The anode is always more reactive than the metal it is protecting, so it will grab electrons before the structure it is protecting.

If you want to see what would happen if you didn't use an anode, you could take two pieces of the same metal, and put one in salt water and one in fresh water.  The one in salt water will corrode away much faster than the one in fresh water.

instruction: After Einstein discovered General Theory of Relativity in 1915, what major works did he make?
output_1:
Einstein continued his work on General Relativity, publishing a summary of his results in 1916, and the full development of the theory in 1917. His theory explained gravity as a manifestation of the curvature of spacetime, and predicted that spacetime would be warped by the presence of mass. The theory also predicted that light emitted by a distant star would be deflected by the gravitational field of the Sun, and would therefore appear to come from a slightly different direction than expected. This effect was predicted to be very small, so observing it would require a precise measurement.
In 1919, a British expedition led by Sir Arthur Eddington observed a solar eclipse from the island of Principe, off the west coast of Africa. They measured a small deflection of starlight as predicted by General Relativity, and the results were published in a paper by Eddington and Einstein. This confirmed the validity of General Relativity as a theory of gravity, and established Einstein's reputation as a scientist.
Einstein also made important contributions to quantum mechanics, a theory that describes the behavior of matter and energy on a very small scale. He developed a theory of quantum statistics known as Bose-Einstein statistics, which describes how particles of matter interact with each other. He also developed a theory of photoelectric effect, in which light is absorbed by an electron. This work helped to lay the foundations for quantum theory.
Einstein also made important contributions to the theory of relativity. He developed special relativity, a theory that describes the motion of objects in space and time. He also developed general relativity, a theory that describes the curvature of spacetime caused by the presence of matter and energy.
output_2:
Einstein spent the next five years working on the general theory of relativity, with a brief interruption in the summer of 1916 when he developed the basis of what was to become quantum theory. This work culminated in the publication of the Annus Mirabilis papers in November 1918. These papers, written in collaboration with Grossmann and Mehler, and with Einstein himself as the sole author of the first paper, presented original research on five major topics in physics:

*  the derivation of the inertial force from the field equations of gravitation,
*  the formulation of the general theory of relativity,
*  a statistical explanation of the diffusion of gases,
*  a theory of the specific heats of solids, and
*  a new explanation of the quantum theory, based on the hypothesis that the radiation field and the electromagnetic field are identical.

Einstein's work during World War I was not limited to theoretical physics, however. In 1917, he published a paper on "the method of theoretical physics," and another on the theory of relativity and its application to mechanical problems. He also worked with his friend and colleague Walther Mayer on a unified field theory that would combine electromagnetism and gravitation. He made significant progress in this area, but was unable to complete it due to his heavy workload.

instruction: Can a company ask you to leave, push you for an exit date, say they “cannot” lay you off and have to train replacement?

## In the United States

In the United States, it depends on the state and possibly local laws.

The WARN Act also gives the employer the right to recover damages for the cost of the advance notice, if it is proven that the advance notice was not needed. In other states, there may be less stringent or no notice requirements.

An employer cannot be forced to pay severance, other than what is in the employee's contract or employment agreement. If there is no agreement, the employer is not required to pay severance. An employer can also terminate an employee at will, if the state's laws permit. This means that the employer can terminate the employee without cause, and the employee cannot sue the employer for wrongful termination.

## Outside the United States

In most countries, employment is at will, meaning the employer can terminate the employee without cause. An employee cannot sue the employer for wrongful termination, unless there is a collective bargaining agreement or a contract that specifies grounds for termination. In some countries, such as India, there may be a requirement of reasonable notice. For example, in India, the employer is required to provide 15 days' notice or pay in lieu of notice. In some countries, such as Australia, there may be redundancy payments.

instruction: What is a current product that you expect will ultimately fail?
output_1:
A product that I expect to fail is Google Glass. The idea itself is interesting and could have great potential, but Google Glass is too early of a product and has too many technical limitations. I don't expect Google to abandon the product, but I do expect it to fade away as a side project for Google.

For starters, Google Glass isn't really a product yet, just a developer kit. The price tag is quite high for a product that is only available to developers and "Glass Explorers". The Explorers program is also quite exclusive. You have to be referred by an existing Glass Explorer in order to get your own pair.

Glass is also limited in what it can do right now. It doesn't work well in low-light situations, it has no GPS, it can't be submerged in water, and it's not voice controlled. It's not even a complete product. Google hasn't even released Glass to the general public yet, and there's no clear timeline for when it will be released.

Glass is also highly controversial. People have privacy concerns over what Glass can record and send. There are also concerns over how people will use Glass. Some people have already been kicked out of establishments for wearing Glass. There's also a lot of speculation that Google Glass is a stepping stone to a more invasive product like an implantable computer.

So what will happen to Google Glass? It will probably just fade away as a side project for Google. Google has too many other projects that they're focusing on right now to put any more resources into Glass. Glass may never even be released to the general public. It's too early of a product, and it has too many technical limitations. I don't expect Google to abandon the project, but I do expect it to fade away as a side project for Google.

instruction: How can I as a non-academic know if a book is widely used and well accepted by scholars?
output_1:
The answer will depend on your field and subfield. The books that I use in my work in Classics would not be appropriate for someone doing work in Chemistry or Computer Science. I will provide examples of how you can research a specific book in Classics to get an idea of how to research a book in your field. 

## The first step: Look at the author

If the author of the book is well-known and well-respected in your field, then you can probably assume that the book is good. Look at the author's website and see if they have a list of their publications, or if they have a CV (curriculum vitae). If the author has published a lot of good work, then it's likely that their book is good as well. You can also check to see if the author has won any awards or honors in your field.

## The second step: Look at the book's publisher

The publisher of the book can also give you an idea of its quality. Major university presses, such as the University of California Press, University of Chicago Press, and Oxford University Press, are likely to publish good quality books. Smaller presses, such as university or college presses, may be less reliable. You can also check to see if the book is available in a digital format, and if so, see if there are any reviews of the book online.

## The third step: Read the book

If you can, read the book yourself to see if it's useful to you. Look at the table of contents and see if the book covers the material that you need. Read the introduction and see if the author presents their arguments clearly and logically. Read a few chapters and see if the book is well-written and engaging. If you have access to the book in a digital format, you may also be able to read the book's endnotes and bibliography. These can give you an idea of the book's sources and whether the author has done their research properly.

## The fourth step: Talk to other scholars in your field

If you know other scholars in your field, ask them if they have read the book and what they think of it. They may be able to tell you whether it's widely used and well-accepted by other scholars. You can also look for reviews of the book in scholarly journals in your field. These reviews will usually be written by other scholars and will give you an idea of the book's quality.
output_2:
Let's start with the last bit first:

*   The book's Amazon sales ranking is probably a good indication of its popularity (at least among the general public). You can find this number on the book's Amazon page.
*   You can check if the book is indexed in Google Scholar. You'll see a link to Google Scholar results on the book's Amazon page, but you can also check manually if the book is indexed:
    *   Go to Google Scholar's home page
    *   Click on "Settings" (gear icon on the top right)
    *   Under "Library links", add the link for the book's Amazon page.
    *   Search for the book in Google Scholar and check if it shows up in the results. If it does, you're good to go.

Now for the second part:

*   You can ask professors in your field of interest (if you know any) what books they recommend.
*   You can check if the book has been reviewed in scholarly journals. Google Scholar should be able to help you with this.
*   You can check if the book is listed in library catalogs such as WorldCat.

3. Native Americans don't pay taxes. Native Americans pay state and federal income taxes, as well as sales and property taxes.
4. Native Americans live in teepees. Native Americans traditionally lived in various types of dwellings, depending on their environment. These included longhouses, pit houses, wigwams, and earth lodges.
5. Native Americans only eat buffalo. Native Americans ate a variety of foods, including game animals, fish, and wild plants.

instruction: How should I do time manage spreading time working on multiple projects? For example, should I "time block" your calendar and say 8am to 10am I work Project A. And 10am to 11am I work on Project B. What are other methods besides time blocking?
output_1:
Time management is a very broad topic, and there are many different ways that one could approach it. Here are some tips and tricks that I've found helpful:

* Schedule specific blocks of time for different activities. For example, you could block off time for writing, meetings, and answering emails. This can help you stay focused on the task at hand and avoid getting distracted by other things.
* Set aside time each day for planning. This can be as simple as sitting down with your calendar and deciding what you want to accomplish that day, or it can be more formal, such as using a task management tool to track your goals and priorities.
* Create a to-do list and prioritize the tasks. This will help you focus on the most important things first and avoid getting distracted by less important tasks.
* Create a plan for handling interruptions. This could be as simple as deciding that you won't answer emails during certain times of the day, or it could be more involved, such as having a system for responding to emails quickly and efficiently.
* Set aside time for reflection. This could be a few minutes at the end of the day to review what you accomplished and what you want to accomplish the next day, or it could be more formal, such as setting aside time once a week for planning and reflection.

Time management is a skill that can be learned and refined over time. Try out these tips and see what works best for you.
output_2:
Time blocking is a good method for prioritizing your work and protecting your focus. However, it doesn't work for everyone. If you're struggling to get things done, try these other methods:

* Use a to-do list to prioritize your work
* Set a schedule and stick to it
* Create daily and weekly goals
* Don't work late into the night
* Keep an eye on the clock
* Stay focused when you're working
* Learn to say no
* Delegate tasks when you can

If you're feeling overwhelmed, it's important to take a step back and figure out why. Once you've identified the problem, you can start to find solutions that work for you.

instruction: What is the best explanation of Newton’s laws?
output_1:
I'm not a physics expert, but here is my interpretation of Newton's laws.

## Newton's First Law of Motion

An object at rest remains at rest and an object in motion remains in motion with the same speed and in the same direction unless acted upon by an unbalanced force.

## Newton's Second Law of Motion

The rate at which momentum changes is directly proportional to the force applied, and happens in the direction the force is applied.

## Newton's Third Law of Motion

Every action has an equal and opposite reaction.

So if you apply a force to an object, the object applies an equal and opposite force back to you. If you push on a wall, the wall pushes back on you. If you throw a ball in the air, the ball applies a force to your hand as it leaves your hand, and you apply a force to the ball as it leaves your hand.
output_2:
Newton’s laws describe the relationship between an object’s mass, the forces acting on it, and its acceleration.

Forces are pushes or pulls that act on an object, and they can be described in terms of force vectors. For example, the force of gravity on Earth is a vector pointing towards the center of the planet, with a magnitude that depends on the object’s mass and the gravitational constant.

The first law of motion says that a body will continue in a state of uniform motion unless acted upon by a force. In other words, objects will stay moving at a constant speed in a straight line unless something changes the direction or magnitude of the forces acting on them. The second law describes how acceleration changes when a force is applied, and the third law states that for every action, there is an equal and opposite reaction.

instruction: I'm buying a car for the first time, any advice?
output_1:
Congratulations on your new purchase! Buying a car is a big step, but it doesn't have to be overwhelming. Here are a few tips to help make the process go smoothly:

* Research: Before you even start looking at cars, it's important to do some research. Take a look at different makes and models, read reviews, and compare prices. This will help you narrow down your options and find the car that's right for you.
* Test drive: Once you've found a few cars that you're interested in, it's time to take them for a test drive. This is the best way to get a feel for the car and see if it's right for you.
* Negotiate: Once you've found the car you want, it's time to start negotiating. Don't be afraid to haggle a little - you may be surprised at how much money you can save.
* Inspect: Before you sign anything, make sure to have the car inspected by a mechanic. This will help you avoid any unexpected surprises down the road.
* Financing: If you're not paying cash for the car, make sure to get financing in place before you sign anything. This will help you avoid any delays in getting your new car.

Remember, buying a car doesn't have to be complicated. With a little research and negotiation, you can get the car you want at a price you can afford. Good luck!
output_2:
## Buying a car - general advice

If you are buying a new car, there are lots of websites that can help you compare different models, prices, and features. You might want to look at Edmunds, or the websites of the major manufacturers (Honda, Toyota, etc).

If you are buying a used car, you might want to check out the Blue Book value, or check Craigslist, Autotrader, or other websites where people are selling cars. You should also check the car's history (CarFax is a good website for this), and make sure it's not a lemon (a car with lots of problems that the manufacturer or seller is trying to get rid of).

You should also check your credit report to make sure there aren't any errors that could affect your ability to get a loan. If you don't already have a loan, you should check your credit score, and try to improve it if it's low.

When you go to the dealership, you might want to ask the salesperson to walk you through the features of the car, and make sure you understand how everything works. You should also ask them to show you the owner's manual, and make sure you understand the warranty.

If you're buying the car from a private seller, you might want to ask them to take you for a test drive, and have a mechanic check the car out before you buy it.

instruction: Are there parallels between the use of radio communication by nationalists in the 1930’s and the use of social media/Twitter by nationalists in the present day? Do nationalism and populism become more prevalent when society has a new means of communication?
output_1:
The short answer is yes.

In the 1930s, the primary means of mass communication in most countries was radio. Like the modern internet, it was a relatively inexpensive and easy-to-use technology that allowed people to communicate over long distances. However, it also allowed for the dissemination of propaganda and misinformation, which was used to great effect by both fascist and communist groups.

As with the internet today, radio was a powerful tool for disseminating propaganda. Both the Nazis and the communists used radio to promote their ideologies, spread disinformation, and mobilize their supporters. For example, the Nazis used radio to spread their antisemitic propaganda and to mobilize support for their policies. Similarly, the communists used radio to spread their communist propaganda and to mobilize support for their policies.

In addition to propaganda, radio was also used to spread disinformation. For example, the Nazis and the communists both used radio to spread false rumors and conspiracy theories, which served to sow division and confusion among their opponents.

In conclusion, nationalism and populism can be fuelled by new means of communication, and the 1930s saw the rise of both nationalism and populism fuelled by the new means of communication at the time - radio.
output_2:
There are similarities, but also some major differences. 
* Similarities:
  * The radio and Twitter are both very good at spreading information quickly to a wide audience. 
  * Both Twitter and radio are very good at disseminating information that is attractive to the target group, but that might be perceived as biased or untrue by other groups. 
  * Both Twitter and radio can be used to spread propaganda and disinformation. 
  * Both Twitter and radio are very good at reinforcing one's own view and amplifying one's own voice. 
* Differences: 
  * In the 1930s, the radio was a new and relatively unknown technology. People had to listen to radio broadcasts, they could not choose what to listen to or when to listen. This meant that radio broadcasts could reach a very large audience, but it was difficult to target specific groups. On the other hand, Twitter is a very targeted form of communication. People choose what to read, and can ignore everything else. This means that Twitter can be used to spread very specific and targeted messages to very specific groups, but it is much more difficult to reach a large audience. 
  * Twitter has a very short lifetime. A tweet can only live for a few hours, and then it is gone forever. Radio broadcasts can live on forever. This means that Twitter is very good at spreading a quick and short message, but it is much less good at spreading long-term propaganda.
